    <title>Group theory</title>
    <link href="https://idealine9.github.io/posts/Group-Theory/"/>
    <id>https://idealine9.github.io/posts/Group-Theory/</id>
    <published>2023-08-22T03:03:20.441Z</published>
    <updated>2023-08-31T08:43:45.905Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>MCS的一点阅读笔记 <span id="more"></span></p><h3 id="vertex-degrees">10.1 Vertex Degrees</h3><p>The <strong><em><span class="math inline">\(in {-} degree \(d^-)\)</span></em></strong> is the number of arrows coming into it (<em>number of times the vertex is pointed</em> ),</p><p>similarly, the <strong><em><span class="math inline">\(out{-}degree \(d^+)\)</span></em></strong> is the number of arrows out of it (<em>number of points to other vertices</em> ).</p><p>If <strong><span class="math inline">\(G\)</span></strong> is a<strong>digraph</strong> and <span class="math inline">\(v \inV(G)\)</span> , then <span class="math display">\[\sum_{v \ \in \ V(G)} d^+(v) = \sum_{v \ \in \ V(G)} d^-(v)\]</span> and both sums are equal to <strong><em><spanclass="math inline">\(\vert E(G) \vert\)</span></em></strong></p><h3 id="walks-and-paths">10.2 Walks and Paths</h3><blockquote><p><strong>Definition</strong>.</p><p><strong><span class="math inline">\(walk\)</span></strong> : A<strong><span class="math inline">\(walk\)</span></strong> in a digraphis an alternating sequence of vertices and edges that begins with avertex and ends with a vertex.</p><p><strong><span class="math inline">\(closed \ walk\)</span></strong> :A <strong><span class="math inline">\(closed \ walk\)</span></strong> isa <span class="math inline">\(walk\)</span> that begins and ends at thesame vertex.</p><p><strong><span class="math inline">\(path\)</span></strong> : The<span class="math inline">\(walk\)</span> is a <strong><spanclass="math inline">\(path\)</span></strong> if and only if all thevertices are different.</p><p><strong><span class="math inline">\(cycle\)</span></strong> : A<strong><span class="math inline">\(cycle\)</span></strong> is apositive length <span class="math inline">\(path\)</span> and begins andends at the same vertex.</p></blockquote><blockquote><p><strong>Lemma</strong>. [ The Triangle Inequality ]</p></blockquote><p><span class="math display">\[dist(u,v) \le dist(u,x)+dist(x,v)\]</span></p><p>for all vertices <span class="math inline">\(u,\ v, \ x\)</span> withequality holding if and only if <span class="math inline">\(x\)</span>is on a shortest path from <span class="math inline">\(u\)</span> to<span class="math inline">\(v\)</span>.</p><h3 id="adjacency-matrices">10.3 Adjacency Matrices</h3><p>If a graph <strong><span class="math inline">\(G\)</span></strong>has <strong><span class="math inline">\(n\)</span></strong> vertices<strong><span class="math inline">\(v_0, \ v_1 \ ... \v_{n-1}\)</span></strong> , a useful way to represent it is with an<strong><span class="math inline">\(n \times n\)</span></strong> matrixof zeros and ones called its <strong><em>adjacencymatrices</em></strong> <span class="math inline">\(A_G\)</span>.</p><p><strong><span class="math inline">\((A_G)_{ij}\)</span></strong> is<span class="math inline">\(1\)</span> if there is an edge from vertex<strong><em><span class="math inline">\(v_i\)</span></em></strong> tovertex <strong><em><spanclass="math inline">\(v_j\)</span></em></strong> and <spanclass="math inline">\(0\)</span> otherwise. <spanclass="math display">\[(A_G)_{ij}=\begin{cases}1 &amp; if \ \langle v_i \to v_j \rangle \in E(G),\\0 &amp; otherwise,\end{cases}\]</span></p><p>Let <strong><span class="math inline">\(H\)</span></strong> be the4-node graph. Its <strong><em>adjacency matrix</em></strong> <spanclass="math inline">\(A_H\)</span> is the 4 <spanclass="math inline">\(\times\)</span> 4 matrix : <spanclass="math display">\[A_H \ = \ \ \\begin{array}{}&amp; a &amp; b &amp; c &amp; d \\a &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\b &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 \\c &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\d &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\\end{array}\]</span> We can use <strong>matrix powers</strong> to count numbers ofwalks between vertices. For example, if we want to know the walk with alength of <span class="math inline">\(2\)</span>, we could have readthese counts from the entires in the matrix <strong><spanclass="math inline">\((A_H)^2\)</span></strong> : <spanclass="math display">\[(A_H)^2 \ = \ \ \\begin{array}{}&amp; a &amp; b &amp; c &amp; d \\a &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\b &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\c &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 \\d &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\\end{array}\]</span> More generally, the matrix <strong><spanclass="math inline">\((A_G)^k\)</span></strong> provides a count of thenumber of <strong>length <span class="math inline">\(k\)</span>walks</strong> between vertices in any digraph <strong><spanclass="math inline">\(G\)</span></strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Theorem</strong>. For a digraph <spanclass="math inline">\(G\)</span>, if <spanclass="math inline">\(C\)</span> is the <em>length-m walk countingmatrix</em> and <span class="math inline">\(D\)</span> is the<em>length-n walk counting matrix</em>, then <spanclass="math inline">\(CD\)</span> is the <em>length k+m walk countingmatrix</em> for <span class="math inline">\(G\)</span>.</p></blockquote><blockquote><p><strong>Corollary</strong>. The <em>length-k counting matrix of adigraph</em> <span class="math inline">\(G\)</span> is <spanclass="math inline">\((A_G)^k\)</span> , for all <spanclass="math inline">\(k\in\)</span> <spanclass="math inline">\(\mathbb{N}\)</span>.</p></blockquote><p>In other words, you can determine the number of <strong><em>length<span class="math inline">\(k\)</span> walks</em></strong> between anypair of vertices simply by <strong>computing the <spanclass="math inline">\(k\)</span> th power</strong> of the<strong><em>adjacency matrix</em></strong>.</p><h4 id="shortest-path">10.3.1 Shortest Path</h4><p>To find the lengths of all the <strong>shortest paths</strong> in an<em>n-vertex</em> graph <span class="math inline">\(G\)</span> is tocompute the successive powers of <spanclass="math inline">\(A_G\)</span> one by one <strong>up to the <spanclass="math inline">\(n-1\)</span> times</strong>, watching for the<strong>first power</strong> at which each entry becomes<strong>positive</strong>.</p><p>The distance from <span class="math inline">\(u\)</span> to <spanclass="math inline">\(v\)</span> will be the smallest value <spanclass="math inline">\(k\)</span> for which <spanclass="math inline">\((A_G)^K_{uv}\)</span> is nonzero, and if there isa shortest path, its length will be <span class="math inline">\(\len-1\)</span> . The methods apply as well to <strong><em>weightedgraphs</em></strong>.</p><h3 id="walks-relations">10.4 Walks Relations</h3><p>For any digraph <span class="math inline">\(G\)</span>, a binaryrelation <strong><span class="math inline">\(G^*\)</span></strong>,called the walk relation on <span class="math inline">\(V(G)\)</span>,where <span class="math display">\[u \ G^* \ v ::= \text{there is a walk in $G$ from $u$ to $v$}\]</span></p><h3 id="directed-acyclic-graphsdag-scheduling">10.5 Directed AcyclicGraphs(DAG) &amp; Scheduling</h3><blockquote><p><strong>Definition</strong>. A <em><strong>directed acyclic</strong>graph</em> (DAG) is a directed graph with no cycles.</p></blockquote><blockquote><p><strong>Definition</strong>. A <strong><em>topologicalsort</em></strong> of a <strong>finite</strong> DAG is a list of all thevertices such that each vertex <span class="math inline">\(v\)</span>appears earlier in the list than every other vertex reachable form <spanclass="math inline">\(v\)</span>.</p></blockquote><blockquote><p><strong>Definition</strong>.</p><ol type="1"><li>A vertex <span class="math inline">\(v\)</span> of a DAG <spanclass="math inline">\(G\)</span> is <strong><em>minimum</em></strong> ifand only if every other vertex is reachable from <spanclass="math inline">\(v\)</span>.</li><li>A vertex <span class="math inline">\(v\)</span> of a DAG <spanclass="math inline">\(G\)</span> is <strong><em>minimal</em></strong> ifand only if <span class="math inline">\(v\)</span> is not reachable fromany other vertex.</li></ol></blockquote>]]></content>
    
    
